<br>
March 7, 2003 - When Paul Robinson, CEO of Animal Motor Works, applied to the New Hampshire State Police Explosives License Division for a &quot;state&quot; storage permit for Ammonium Perchlorate Composite Propellant (APCP) propellant cartridges, the State Police found that APCP didn't fit into any of their assigned explosive categories. Consequently, the State Police decided to conduct their own tests to classify the propellant and asked for Robinson's most reactive propellant. He gave the State Police three APCP propellant grains that were each three inches in size.<br>
<br>
In the first test, the State Police put a boosted blasting cap in one propellant grain and initiated the cap. There was no explosion besides the blasting cap. The cap simply scattered pieces of APCP in a five to six foot radius.<br>
<br>
In the second test, the State Police wrapped an APCP propellant cartridge with detonator cord. The cord was initiated with no explosion or ignition of the APCP grain. The detonator cord simply cut the APCP grain in half. The State Police then took one of the halves and wrapped that half with detonator cord. Again, the detonator cord failed to ignite the APCP or cause it to explode. It simply cut the half into smaller pieces.<br>
<br>
Finally, the State Police took the small pieces from the previous tests and threw them into a small fire. The APCP did not explode but simply burned in the fire. The New Hampshire State Police Explosives License Division was completely satisfied that APCP was not an explosive or blasting agent. Consequently, they granted Paul Robinson a storage permit for his APCP propellant cartridges. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/8/03 3:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  AP Newswire omission</span><hr size=1> John Wickman is a good leader.  He is very honest, sees the issues as a engineer would, and works tirelessly for the good of everyone in the hobby - not just LP (Estes), or the certified HPR community (Tripoli, NAR).  I am a member an support the efforts of Tripoli, NAR and ARSA - I think the certification programs have done alot to make the hobby safe.  But I can see that John is foremost in his commitment to everyone, and I am quite annoyed that he is not getting the cooperation from the other organizations duirng this crisis.<br>
<br>
Look at the awareness phenomena.  Tripoli and NAR have not been very useful in keeping people informed, while the ARSA sites at <br>
<br>
     <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.space-rockets.com/arsanews.html">www.space-rockets.com/arsanews.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
     <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.space-rockets.com/homeland.html">www.space-rockets.com/homeland.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
and  <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.space-rockets.com/congress.html">www.space-rockets.com/congress.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
have contain extremely powerful information that every rocketeer should know.  But in the AP Newswire interview, no reference to the ARSA webpages was included at the end. Tripoli and NAR sites do not hav this information, so its exclusion in the AP article was irresponsible. a disservice to the effort and all rocketeers who need to have the best information available.<br>
<br>
I don't understand how politics can supersede effectiveness.<br>
<br>
